<subSubSection id="C36696BB8E58FFB5FF1AFF31DBADFE8A" pageId="3" pageNumber="144" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E58FFB5FF1AFF31DBADFE8A" blockId="3.[163,1071,202,364]" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">
Comment: Species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E58FFB5FE70FF31DBA7FF06" authority="HEYDEN 1870" authorityName="HEYDEN" authorityYear="1870" box="[457,730,202,224]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Piochardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90819228E58FFB5FE70FF31DB46FF39" box="[457,571,202,223]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">Piochardia</emphasis>
HEYDEN 1870
</taxonomicName>
are associated with ants of the genus 
<emphasis id="B90819228E58FFB5FF53FF1DD819FF1D" box="[234,356,230,251]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">Cataglyphis</emphasis>
FÖRSTER. The previously known distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E58FFB5FCC0FF1CDA86FF1D" baseAuthorityName="FAUVEL" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[889,1019,230,252]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Piochardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oberthuri">
<emphasis id="B90819228E58FFB5FCC0FF1CDA86FF1D" box="[889,1019,230,252]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">P. oberthuri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confined to North Africa from 
<collectingCountry id="F36B85A08E58FFB5FE51FEF9DB49FEFE" box="[488,564,258,280]" name="Algeria" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">Algeria</collectingCountry>
in the west to 
<collectingCountry id="F36B85A08E58FFB5FD6FFEF9DA6CFEFE" box="[726,785,258,280]" name="Libya" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">Libya</collectingCountry>
in the east (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEDB8C18E58FFB5FC2FFEF9DD5EFEFE" author="ASSING V" box="[918,1059,258,280]" pageId="3" pageNumber="144" pagination="277 - 301" refId="ref7054" refString="ASSING V. (1999): A revision of the genus Piochardia HEYDEN, 1870 (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). - Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien 101 B: 277 - 301." type="journal article" year="1999">ASSING 1999</bibRefCitation>
). The above specimen considerably expands the distribution towards the east. It was found in association with 
<emphasis id="B90819228E58FFB5FED2FEC1DB25FEA9" box="[363,600,314,335]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="144">Cataglyphis holgerseni</emphasis>
COLLINGWOOD &amp; AGOSTI 1996 (det. Sharaf). The nest was built in sandy dry soil under a large rock.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
